snippet.textDisplay:
Jim needs to man up and hold Boeing to the same standards and safety regulations as they do with SpaceX. Had SpaceX failed to reach and dock with the ISS, it would have been a re-flight for sure and we'd be anywhere between 2 to 5 months further for another attempt. As good as this test was by recovering Starliner safely, the Commercial Crew Program was set up as replacement for the Space Shuttle to bring astronauts to the ISS and back for the foreseeable future.

NASA's preferential treatment by skipping objectives might just put lives at risk, something they are actually trying to avoid, so they say. It's good to see Starliner achieve the remainder of the mission, but another demonstration mission should be a requirement.

snippet.textDisplay: I appreciate the optimism of the hosts. Wow, they really know how to spin a story. Not once did I hear any mention that the reason we were even having this landing was because Starliner failed to reach the correct orbit. Focusing on 3! main parachutes, it was said at least five times that there were 3 chutes, this of course is to make us forget about the third chute failure during the pad abort test, that or they were surprised that all three worked also. I realize that Boeing has done amazing things for aerospace in the past, but we're moving into the future and Boeing can't keep up the pace. They spend more money, take much longer and up to this point nothing has worked 100%. I feel if this contract had been for moving a pile of sand, Boeing would want millions, hire 20,000 people, have each one pick up a single grain at a time and the project would take 10 years and be over-budget with sand left on the ground, SpaceX would go to Dollar General and buy a shovel, move the pile, be done in 10 minutes, and be able to reuse the shovel!

snippet.textDisplay: Why does it feel like we're watching stock footage from the 60's-70's. Its 2020 people, and we're supposed to get all giddy about a parachute landing in the middle of the friggin desert? "21st century" spaceships can do powered, controlled landings back at the launch pad! I'm sad for these engineers crying over some supposedly great achievement. We've been landing "capsules" back on earth for over 60 years! So in all that time all they have accomplished is the addition of "bigger" chutes and an airbag which is NOT new tech just a new application. This is an absolute waste of taxpayer funds and frankly an embarrassment for the advancement of American Space technology. Yet it only took private industry less than 10 years to perfect controlled repulsive landing technology at a 3rd the cost of a bloated government contractor. It's time we tell our Representatives to make a change in Space technology funding.
